title: Wayne Dalton Garage door opener coupler

description.text:
My coupler on my garage door opener broke, and after searching for one online, i was only met with "This part is no longer in stock" everywhere, so I did the next best thing and made my own.

This is for... I dont know the model, but its got a timing belt drive, not a standard roller chain.

Print at 100% infill, obviously, as this part will undergo a fair amount of stress. Use something high strength. For ease, I used PLA, printed at ~210C and overextruded at 105%, just to make sure it was as solid as could be.
Print with supports, just right in the center.

After, run to your local hardware store and pick up the correct size bronze bushing, i believe its 11/16" (or 5/8") x some ID x 1" or 1.15", ram jam it into the center hole and re-assemble. Youre back in business.

The first one i made i printed vertically as pictured (probably not as the model displayed tho), at 70% infill, and due to me not setting the limits correctly, it broke, as soon as it touched down into the floor.
Dont be like me, play it safe, print it at 100% infill and lay it on its side (so they layers go the long way) and make sure your door is setup correctly.

Would the first print have survived had i had the door set correctly? The world may never know. All I do know is that i made this at the end of July 2016, and as of mid Nov 2016, its still working.

Update: Sept 3, 2017. Still working. :)

Just another thumb nut screw thing for your printer or router or whatever.

title: Rostock Max V3/HE280 Slim Fan duct

description.text:
This will not work with the autocal on the v3 or an enclosure, fyi
For an improvement on Norcorgi's design (and one that works with autocal/enclosure), check out this one.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2058092

Nov 18, 2016 - V2/not the first crappy one released.
Removed some material, now its 1mm thick all around (perfect for 2 passes of that .5mm nozzle that comes with the HE280. reduced weight and matl, as well as print time.
Also did a bridge test (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12925), except it didnt print the circle. The first one was the first one i printed, along the Y axis, the second was along the X. The Y is supposed to be 1mm thick, but measures 1.9, slight sag on the first layer (or 2), but the top is flat as it should be.
Nov 17/16/whenever - First crappy release.

Work in progress!
The first one i printed was slightly too small for the fan, so im currently making a new, larger one. Stay tuned for results/new files.

I am open to any comments on this. Good, Bad, indifferent, I don't care. If you think its bad and should be changed, Let me know! If you like it, but have some additional ideas, Let me know!

A 'slim' fan duct I made for my HE280 hotend. The part layer fan mounts that it comes with are crap and cant bridge at all, simply because they dont point towards the nozzle. Sure, there are 3, but its not enough. To use this, however, you will need to cut the protruding tab things off your effector platform. I used a dremel (but just a bit at a time, as it will melt) to get it close, then cleaned up with a metal file.

Could i have just picked up 3 squirrel cage style fan/blowers? Yes. But I already had the 3 axial fans that came with the hotend. Why buy something when youve got a printer to make it?

I saw this design here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1792867
Its nice, but the dynamics of it are pretty bad. So I decided to make my own with some nice round sweeping corners, and here it is.

Use 1, use 3, do whatever. I dont care. Youre probably an adult, right?

By design, this will be very, very, very close to touching your part (and may, depending on how far your nozzle sticks out. If it does, print up a little round spacer/washer (or buy a few) to lift it up (goes under the screw). If you raise it too much, it may interfere with the end of the arms, or the effector platform. Simply grab a file and remove a bit of interfering material.

Once ive got this complete, and everything dialed in, ill probably post some more pics and bridging test pics.

title: Geeetech Al. Rear Mounted Radial Fan Shroud

description.text:
Update 19 Mar 2017
Some people complain that the bracket for the fan is fragile. Redesigned both the shroud & bracket to give more strength for the fixing area. Also added a slot for the fixing nut/s and made the adjustable area bigger.
Files to use are FixingBracketV7 & MainShroudV8Round

Update 7 Dec 2016
Added 2 files - MainShroudV6.stl & FixingBracketV5.stl.
These files allow for two screws to be used for fixing to provide a more secure and stable fixing mechanism.
Note: This shroud may not fit with the original 33mm throat as there is not much clearance with this throat between the end of the X bracket and the bed. It fits perfectly with anyone who has upgraded to a 50mm throat.

When my Geeetech Al. extruder throat got blocked, I purchased a 50mm replacement. The original was 33mm and only Geeetech sold these at a premium. What this did was give me an additional height for the end of the nozzle of about 17mm. This also gave me a bigger gap between the end of the Z axis bearing bracket and the bed.

My original design used a normal fan with a circular shroud. But given that these fans are so under powered the cooling was inadequate. I read that Radial fans gave more air output. Also the design of the shroud in front of the extruder, hid my nozzle when printing.

To solve these 2 problems and now that I had the height to play around with, I designed this fan shroud to fit to the BACK of the X axis steel bracket and also to use a Radial fan.

After much testing this is the model I have come up with and fitted & it does push more air with less noise. This fan whine was more noticeable ever since the printer itself went silent after fitting these: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1798758

The bracket is designed to allow X movement for adjustment and the fan shroud itself allows adjustment in the Z direction so that an ideal location can be attained.

Since anyone printing this obviously needs cooling, and PLA does not behave when not cooled, I also included a dummy "helper" object.

Sketchup files included in case you need to tweak the design.

Printer:

Geeetech Full Metal Aluminum

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

It is best that the fan shroud is placed at one corned and the "helper" object at the diagonally opposite corner. This gives the part enough time to cool down while other parts are being printed. It takes longer but the results are worth it. Also the fan shroud is rotated about 33 degrees to the left (see image). The reason this is because if you do not already have cooling, there is bridging to be done as the inside of the shroud is hollow and rotating it and printing this way allows for the smallest bridging.

Please see the image of the build plate attached to see how to position/rotate the objects for printing.

You can fix the shroud with a 3mm bolt+nut or a 3mm bolt and this item embedded into the bracket - https://www.aliexpress.com/item/100Pcs-Lot-M3-3-M3-x-3-Brass-Insert-Nut-Thumb-Brass-Knurled-Round-Nut-Injection/32438775666.html if you print the version with the single hole.

I bought this fan:
http://www.ebay.com.au/itm/Black-Brushless-DC-Cooling-Blower-Fan-2-Wires-5015S-12V-0-14A-50x15mm-/281859519472?hash=item41a022f3f0:g:FpAAAOSwsFpWSxcI

Notice it has a ridge on one end and the shroud is designed for a press fit.

Hi - this is a simple attachment to put a pressure pack spray can on the end of a pole. I use it to reach high into the branches of our fruit trees to zap the odd bug or two - you could also use it for spraying wasps or paint or pretty much anything you don't want to get close to.  
The spray can fits into the rings, then attach a piece of light line to pull the trigger and spray away.  
Originally I printed the socket piece with an ACME thread however the plastic split on the first test (if you look closely at the photo you'll see its held together with a cable tie). Eventually just went with a 1" un-threaded socket for an ordinary broomstick - simple and strong.

Print one of everything, and two of the rings then assemble with seven M5 x 25mm or 3/16 x 1" bolts. If you rotate the pieces around everything can be printed without support except for the socket - 20% infill and wall thickness of 3 will give it a bit of strength.  
Add a 1" broomstick and use a small screw or a nail to hold it in place. Tie on about 6 feet of light line to finish it off.

Jigsaw puzzle made from an L-System drawing from the system:
PREMISE : YXF
Rule 1: X=X+FY
Rule 2: Y=X-FF
Angle: 60Â°
Now, depending on how your Lsystem program evaluates these rules you may or may not end up with the same drawing. But I have confidence in the programmers over at sidefx.com (the make the movie special effects program Houdini that's been instrumental in creating fx for a bajillion movies)

There are several layers of clues on the board and the puzzle pieces themselves. I can solve the Gen7 one in about 15 minutes and the Gen8 in about 3 hours. In the file the layers are labled and pretty straight forward, I think.
Please let me know if anything's mucked up. I reccomend using:
  • 1/8" thick (or there abouts) transparent or translucent acrylic for the puzzle (or you may want to make the pieces out of wood and sand down the hard edges)
  • 1/4" thick MDF for the backing. Or you can just play with it on a flat surface. It's a little unweidly that way though.
    • To bolt the two layers together you'll want:
  • Four 1/4" carriage bolts 1/2"-3/4" long (preferably zinc plated)
  • Four 1/4" wing nuts
    • Also, be careful, the edges are sharp.
    They were initially designed to fit 2 by 3 snugly on an 18" by 24" laser bed.

Print PLA! I've created a version of Lawsy's fan duct (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:30828) that eliminates hotspots for square extruder versions of the Solidoodle 3. This still provides strong airflow across the nozzle for PLA printing without the risk of melting. Lawsy's duct is great if you've upgraded your nozzle or have the circular version. If your SD3 is like mine, you'll find it often melts. This version solves that issue.

description.text:
Design of a ultra compact quadcopter for carrying an action cam ( xiaomi yi/gopro tested)
Its is really small so you can fit it perfectly in a backpack or purse.To take your hero shots everywhere.

Drone design to be connect and go, no worries just fly and record.

In my case I used DYS1306-2300kw and Multistar 1704-1900kv
Esc 12 amp are fit in spaces in the arms.

The battery is being keep in place with a velcro strap as this drone is not for acrobatics but for smooth and calm flying.
Recommended size 1000-1300mah 3s

Propeller size anything from 5 inch to under. 5030 DAL prop in my test.

The camera is being hold in place by an elastic band putted trough the holes of the frame and keep in place with knots.The frame has the size of the camera so it keeps it in place perfectly safe.

The inside space is quite big so you can fit almost any flight controller. From50x50mm size and under.I have even tested with the HKPro Multiwii and fits exactly.

For the controller i used a bluetooth module and even has space enough to put a gps to lock the positions while shooting.

title: NEMA17 to NEMA23 adapter with threaded holes

description.text:
A simple to use NEMA17 to NEMA23 adapter I've made for myself to change my motor.

The extra in it is that it has threaded holes, so you will only need the M3 and M5 screws.
Crazy idea to exclude the nuts, but it works surprisingly good!

Printed out from PLA, with 0.125mm layer height, and the screws hold the big NEMA23 in place nicely.

Do not use an electric screwdriver!
Unless you print this out of metal, of course. :)

(Note: When I printed my version, I did not bother running out the white filament when changing to black, so the first layer is white, and the rest is black. The blackness is barely visible on the photo, but the first white layer is there. And as you can see, the NEMA23 does not have all holes for 4 screws. Only 2 screws are holding it to the adapter)

description.text: This is a replacement part for the base of the Daphine lamp by the company Lumina, designer: Cimini. I found out that the lamp I inherited from my parents is a design classic from the late 70s. Being so old, the plastic base had broken. I remodeled and 3d-printed a new one.

The sockets where the screws have to fit came out a bit too tight off the printer so when I screwed them in some of them delaminated (broke off). I left it that way because the connection is still solid but you might want to make the holes for the screws a bit bigger so it doesn't happen for you.

description.text:
The indicator stalk off my Fiat 850 SC was broken. Because it had an interior metal insert, I was able to expose part of that insert and fit a new end piece.
Printed in PLA, sanded and polished. I won't be gluing it in place because I want to print a version in ABS/ASA .
Update: as would be expected, after a day in the sun the stalk started melting and lost its form.
The temperature inside a car can easily get to 80ºC, softening the plastic just enough for it to start bending.
Not quitting, I made a new version with a stainless steel insert (from a wiper blade).

Update:
In order to insert the stainless steel backbone, I paused printing at 1.8mm (1.9mm should be better). The first try didn't work out, as the part eventually split.
In order to solve the issue I increased flow by 5% after pausing, and increased temperature by 5º throughout the whole print.

Finishing printed parts

It's just a lot of elbow grease. Start with a coarse file to flatten and remove the most ridges and imperfections, move on to 80 grit paper, 120 grit, ..., finish with steel wool and scotch brite. I added a touch of my finest shoe polish!

title: Noise isolation feet for 2020 corners

description.text:
The cooling fan on my Tronxy X3 resonated through my table and floor in my print room above my living room providing a constant hum. Thought I hearing things for a while. I developed these feet to reduce the vibration and quiet my printer down.

Three thicknesses--1.5, 1.6, and 1.8. Depending on your type of filament used and how much flex you might need. 1.6 should be good for most, but if your PLA is too stiff, you can drop down to the 1.5. If the feet seem too soft, you can jump up to the 1.8s.

The 1_5, 1_6, and 1_8 denotes the thickness in mms. Thinner for harder materials.

Printer:

Tronxy X3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm-0.28mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Used two shells.

Higher temp Raptor PLA is a bit softer than bargain PLA and works well with the 1.6 size feet. Stiffer PLA may be better using the 1.5 sized file.

Or could try using thicker ones of the back feet since the weight is more heavily distributed in the rear.

Hopefully your slicer zigzags between the shells making them stiffer. A lower layer height might help.

description.text: Let's face some cold, hard facts. the Messograf caliper pen is not especially practical. It's more of a graduation present for someone going off to architecture school or some technical institute. Nobody expects you to really use it. As a pen, it fares a bit better, but here's the other cold, hard fact. The damn thing's a pain to hold. I feel like I'm holding a small sword that hasn't been sharpened. Sure, you can get ergonomic grips for pens, but the Messograf has that miniature broadsword shape to it, so a premade one isn't going to fit very well, and you'll have to grip it unnaturally tight to make it work.

Printer:

Micro M3D

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

25-60%

Notes:

Printed this twice at different infills. Best advice I can give is obviously the lower the infill the more rubbery/grippy it's going to be. The first one was average infill (no specifics given the M3D application, let's say about 60%) and was a very snug fit; needed both hands and a table to slip it on and off the first time. It got better, but I'd say only go thick if you intend to do more writing than measuring. If you're going to switch between frequently, I'd suggest either a lower infill or even scaling it up by a hair.

I don't recommend making it hollow, however. Unless you can put a horizontal layer in the middle of it, it's likely to fall apart if you grip it too tightly.
Merely 3 primitives, some smart scaling, and a few fillets. The only drawback is you can't use the caliper pen to measure itself... unless you have two ;P

title: Pulsing Puberty Heart
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I designed this pulsing heart for my daughter hitting currently puberty. It pulses slowly with nearly 60 Hz. If a person is approaching, the pulse quickens. At a distance below 30 cm its really running wild. See the video:https://youtu.be/7WT9LreD2JA
The distance to a person (or thing) is measured by means of ultrasonic, the whole circuit is based on a mini-arduino I designed myself. The schematic and PCB design files are included either. The ultrasonic part is based on the popular module HC-SR04 which I modified a little bit to fit on my circuit. I exchanged the angulated 4pin header to a straight one. Now the module can easily plugged in my board.
The 22 LEDs are 5050 RGB NeoPixels from Adafruit. A LDR is integrated to measure the environmental light and control the brightness of the LEDs. As mikrocontroller I used a TQFP AtmelMega328. Take care to flash an arduino bootloader onto the chip before you solder it. To program the chip a 5 pin interface (just 5 SMD pads) is integrated on which a FTDI2USB-breakout board can be adapted via wirewrap strips or cable. The arduino sketch is in the files section.

As power supply I used a 3.7 LiPo 400 mAh cell with JST plug.
Everything fits in the heart shaped case. To wear the heart you can fix with hotmelt a clip from an old button sticker on the backside or use the small ring with a chain.

See also my other NeoPixel project: The NeoPixel Goggles.
